tak.gov.tr/ COVID-19 Turkey Web Portal] on [[T\u00dcB\u0130TAK]]\n* [https://corona.cbddo.gov.tr/ COVID-19 World Map] on the Digital Conversion Office of the President of Republic of Turkey\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Turkey]]\n[[Category:2020 in Turkey|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Turkey"}
{"title_page": "Dark Empire", "text_new": "{{For|the metal band|Dark Empire (band)}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox comics meta series <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title               = Dark Empire\n|image               = Darkempirei.jpg\n|imagesize           = 200\n|caption             = ''Dark Empire I'' (Trade Paperback)\n|alt                 =\n|schedule            = Monthly\n|limited             = y\n|titles              = ''[[#Dark Empire I|Dark Empire I]]''<br />''[[#Dark Empire II|Dark Empire II]]''<br />''[[#Empire's End|Empire's End]]''\n|notable             = y\n|lang                =\n|SciFi               = y\n|Adaptation          =\n|Adapt_link          =\n|publisher           = [[Dark Horse Comics]]\n|date                = '''''Dark Empire I'''''<br />December 1991&nbsp;\u2013 October 1992<br />'''''Dark Empire II'''''<br />December 1994&nbsp;\u2013 May 1995<br />'''''Empire's End'''''<br />October\u2013November 1995\n|issues              = '''''Dark Empire I''''': 6<br />'''''Dark Empire II''''': 6<br />'''''Empire's End''''': 2\n|main_char_team      =\n|writers             = [[Tom Veitch]]\n|artists             = '''''Dark Empire I''''' and '''''Dark Empire II'''''<br />[[Cam Kennedy]]<br />'''''Empire's End'''''<br />[[Jim Baikie]]\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           =\n|colorists           =\n|editors             =\n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            =\n|reprint             =\n|relang              =\n|relang#             =\n|TPB                 = Dark Empire I\n|ISBN                = 1-56971-073-2\n|TPB1                = Dark Empire Trilogy\n|ISBN1               = 1-59582-612-2\n|subcat              = Dark Horse Comics\n|altcat              =\n|alttop              =\n|sort                = Dark Empire\n|addpubcat#          =\n}}\n'''''Dark Empire''''' is a ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[comic book]] [[metaseries]] produced by [[Dark Horse Comics]]. It consists of [[#Dark Empire I|a six-issue]] [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] written by [[Tom Veitch]] and drawn by [[Cam Kennedy]], followed by [[#Dark Empire II|a second six-issue limited series]] by Veitch and Kennedy and [[#Empire's End|a two-issue limited series]] written by Veitch and drawn by [[Jim Baikie]]. The initial series is notable for being one of the very first ''Star Wars'' comics to be produced by Dark Horse Comics, who had acquired the comic rights to the ''Star Wars'' franchise in the early 1990s.\n\nPart of the [[Star Wars expanded to other media|''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe]], the trilogy follows events in the ''Star Wars'' franchise six years after ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Comics Companion|last1=Windham|first1=Ryder|authorlink1=Ryder Windham|last2=Wallace|first2=Daniel|editor1-last=Allie|editor1-first=Scott|editor1-link=Scott Allie|editor2-last=Simpson|editor2-first=Robert|year=2006|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]}}</ref> specifically the aftereffects of [[Timothy Zahn]]'s [[Thrawn trilogy|''Thrawn'' trilogy]]. The story deals with the return of the villainous [[Palpatine]], having successfully cheated death by having his spiritual entity \"reincarnated\" through the essence transfer ritual and cloning technology. Other themes include [[Luke Skywalker]] temporarily succumbing to the dark side of [[the Force]], the official return of [[Boba Fett]] (who had seemingly died after being swallowed by the [[Sarlacc]] in ''Return of the Jedi''), and the first appearance of [[Princess Leia]] and [[Han Solo]]'s son [[Anakin Solo]].\n\n==Publication history==\nThe ''Dark Empire I'' story was originally developed by [[Tom Veitch]] and [[Cam Kennedy]] for [[Marvel Comics]]. Veitch and Kennedy were approached by [[Lucasfilm]] based on their success with ''[[The Light and Darkness War]]''.<ref>''The [[Dark Empire Sourcebook]]'', [[West End Games]], 1st edition, 1993. Horne, Michael, {{ISBN|0-87431-194-2}}</ref><ref>''The Dark Side Sourcebook'', [[Wizards of the Coast]], 1st printing, 2001. Bill Slavicsek, J. D. Wiker, {{ISBN|0-7869-1849-7}}</ref> After difficulties with Marvel, the project was picked up by Dark Horse Comics.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-131/|title= Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #131|first= Brian|last= Cronin|date= November 29, 2007|publisher= Comic Book Resources|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150426232903/http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-131|archivedate= April 26, 2015|url-status=live|quote=  }}</ref>\n\n''Dark Empire I'' was a six-issue limited series published bimonthly in [[1991 in comics|1991]] and [[1992 in comics|1992]], ''Dark Empire II'' was also a six-issue limited series published from [[1994 in comics|1994]] to [[1995 in comics|1995]] and ''Empire's End'', two-issue limited series published in 1995. All three series, plus a sourcebook, would be combined in a hardbound omnibus in 2010.\n\nThe individual comic issues each feature several bonus pages of written context; ''Dark Empire'' for instance details some of Palpatine's history related to his return, including excerpts of books written from his perspective.\n\nThe various series have been collected into [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperbacks]]:\n* ''Dark Empire'' (1993, {{ISBN|1-56971-073-2}})\n* ''Dark Empire II'' (1995, {{ISBN|1-56971-119-4}})\n* ''Empire's End'' (1997, {{ISBN|1-56971-306-5}})\n\nThe entire series has also been collected into a single hardcover:\n* ''Dark Empire Trilogy'' (352 pages, Dark Horse Comics, September 2010, {{ISBN|1-59582-612-2}}, [[Titan Books]], December 2010, {{ISBN|1-84856-887-8}})\n\n==Plot==\n\n===''Dark Empire''===\nSeveral years after the events of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'', the ''[[Millennium Falcon]]'' leads a Rebel task force to [[Coruscant]]. Han Solo, Leia Organa, [[Chewbacca]] and [[C-3PO]] are heading to the planet to rescue [[Luke Skywalker]], R2-D2 and [[Lando Calrissian]], who have spent the past several days holding out against Imperial attacks after an earlier raid using the captured [[Star Destroyer]] ''Liberator'' goes awry and the warship crashes. The Rebels successfully rescue the survivors, but a massive energy storm appears. Luke sees the storm as a large disturbance in [[the Force]], and asks everybody to leave him behind; he lets himself be devoured by the storm.\n\nThe taskforce returns to the Rebel fleet in the Da Soocha system. Rebel commanders discuss the appearance of the Imperials coming out of the Deep Core and discover that Admiral Ackbar's homeworld of Mon Calamari is now under attack by a fleet of Imperial war machines. Called the World Devastators, the machines are designed to convert everything in their path into raw materials for building more war machines on the spot. Lando leads another taskforce with a second captured Star Destroyer leading the charge to aid in Mon Calamari's defense.\n\nMeanwhile, Luke awakes from the light of the Force storm and finds out he is aboard an old Imperial prison ship heading to [[Byss]]. The ship docks and Luke is closely escorted to a chamber, where he is stunned to see [[Emperor Palpatine]] alive. The Emperor explains that he has revived himself in a clone body and makes Luke doubt any attempt to kill him knowing he will quickly manifest in another clone. Sensing the futility and seeing the horror of what is happening in Mon Calamari, Luke humbly surrenders to becoming the Emperor's new apprentice.\n\nLeia has visions of Luke being corrupted into the Dark Side and wants to travel to Byss and save him. She and Han travel to [[Nar Shaddaa]] and try to arrange a ship to bring them past Byss' security network. Han reunites with smuggler friends Shug Ninx, Salla Zend, and Mako Spince to make it happen. Along the way, an old woman named Vima-da-Boda\u2014a former Jedi who survived the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Empire]]'s purge\u2014feels Leia's Force energy and gives her an old Jedi artifact. However, the Hutts have put a large bounty on Han and Leia, with Spince selling him out to [[Boba Fett]] (revealed to have survived being devoured by the Sarlacc during the events of ''Return of the Jedi''); the two escape Nar Shaddaa aboard Salla's ship, the Starlight Intruder, with the Falcon attached. The Intruder has the proper codes to get inside Byss, and Imperial security lets them in (but lock out a pursuing Fett). Han Leia, Chewie, and the droids are brought before Luke and the Emperor.\n\nLeia discovers that he holds hostage an even greater treasure: a mysterious and intelligent artifact called the [[Jedi]] [[Holocron]], a holographic cube that contains historical information about the Jedi. When Leia discovers that the Emperor is interested in possessing her third child, she steals the Holocron and the group successfully breaks out of Byss while having to leave behind Luke again. Luke faces the already frail Emperor and destroys his clone tanks, but the Emperor possesses one living clone and subdues him to his will.\n\nHan's group travels to Mon Calamari as Rebel commando forces lay siege to the World Devastators, which have been shut down by a special master code Luke was able to steal and give to R2 and C3PO for transmission to the machines. The Imperials aboard the machines still have the factories running and attack the Rebels. R2 rigs the World Devastators to destroy each other.\n\nAs the Rebels celebrate on Mon Calamari, Alliance command determines that the World Devastators are part of a larger Imperial offensive to conquer the galaxy. Leia studies the Holocron and sees an old prophecy about a pregnant woman coming to save the Jedi from doom. At the same time, a small Imperial fleet, led by the massive flagship ''Eclipse'', appears above Da Soocha. The Emperor demands that the Alliance surrender Leia to him and Luke. Leia travels on her own and appeals to Luke to break away from the Emperor. Palpatine creates a large Force storm to destroy the Rebel fleet, but Leia and Luke work together to amplify the storm beyond the Emperor's power and turn it against him. The siblings escape the doomed warship, and as Luke sees the last remnants of the Eclipse being vaporized, he declares the Jedi Knights will rise again.\n\n===''Dark Empire II''===\nWith Emperor Palpatine apparently perishing aboard the Eclipse, more worlds defy Imperial edicts, especially those that have been recently reconquered. One of these is the arms manufacturing planet Balmorra, whose planetary governor, Beltane, has begun supplying the Rebels with the latest military vehicles, such as the Viper X1 Automadon, a war droid designed to convert energy from enemy laser fire into power for its own turbolaser cannons. The Emperor's Dark Side Executor Sedriss leads a force to subdue the planet, but Beltane's troops hold the line and Sedriss is compelled to negotiate a supply agreement with him. Sedriss returns to Byss, where he kills two Dark Side Adepts who've been killing other clones of Emperor Palpatine that Luke missed. Palpatine possesses one clone to Sedriss' surprise and orders the Imperial offensive to continue.\n\nHaving pledged to reestablish the Jedi Order by finding any surviving Jedi in the galaxy, Luke Skywalker returns to Pinnacle Base on the moon Da Soocha V (orbiting Da Soocha in the Cyax System of Hutt Space of the Outer Rim) with Kam Solusar, a former Dark Jedi. Beltane tips the [[Rebel Alliance]] of a shipment of new Vipers bound for the Empire's Deep Core stronghold of Byss, and Alliance commanders accept Wedge Antilles' suggestion of intercepting the shipment for a surgical strike using the droids, with Rebel commandos in the attack. Although Luke presses for liberating more worlds to provide more staging areas for an all-out strike on Byss, Mon Mothma asks him to concentrate on rebuilding the Jedi Order instead. The Jedi Holocron educates Luke about the planet Ossus, a former Jedi-populated world destroyed by the Sith thousands of years earlier.\n\nHan, Leia and Chewie fly back to Nar Shaddaa to find Vima-da-Boda, at least where Leia last saw her. However, Vima has disappeared and every bounty hunter on the moon is still out for them, including Boba Fett, as well as an Imperial force led by two Dark Side Elites. Leia successfully fetches Vima after flying into the deeper reaches of Nar Shaddaa. Aboard Nar Shaddaa's traffic control tower, Mako Spince sees Han and guides an Imperial Star Destroyer's tractor beam on him. Han turns the tables by flying close to the tower, forcing the tractor beam to lock onto the structure and pull it instead at full power. The tower impales the Star Destroyer and it crashes into Nar Shaddaa. Fett, back in his old ship Slave I, chases the Millennium Falcon into a nearby acidic gas cloud. Han takes the risk and flies into the cloud, surprisingly appearing on the other side and stumbling onto the long-lost world of Ganath. Ganathan engineers repair the Falcon and equip it with a lightning cannon while the team meets Ganath's ruler, Empatojayos Brand, a veteran Jedi who survived the Empire's Jedi Purge. Inspired by the possibility of a Jedi rebirth, Brand joins Han's party while leaving Ganath in the hands of a military officer. Han takes out Fett and heads to a secret hideout on New Alderaan, where Han and Leia's twin children are under care.\n\nLuke and Kam fly to Ossus and chances upon the Ysanna, a warrior tribe which has rudimentary Force powers. They fight off the Ysanna attacks and sensing they are indeed Jedi, the Ysanna chief welcomes them. Having known about the trip, the Emperor orders Sedriss and fellow Dark Side Elite Vill Goir to capture them. Solusar kills Goir, but Sedriss takes one of the Ysanna hostage and leans against a tree. To everybody's surprise, the tree is a millennia-old Neti Jedi Master named Ood Bnar, who wraps Sedriss in a fatal embrace and they die in an explosion of Force energy. Bnar's heroic sacrifice leaves a part of him in the soil and a hole underneath his location reveals an old cache of lightsabers; Luke successfully discovers an old Jedi library. Two Ysanna tribe members, siblings Ralf and Jem, join Luke and Kam in leaving the planet with their elders' blessing.\n\nLando leads the Rebel infiltration into Byss and start the attack when the Viper droids are offloaded. The droids prove superior to existing Imperial defenses until the Emperor releases an army of Dark Side-mutated monsters on the attackers. The Vipers, which are attuned against energy attacks, are cut to shreds under the monsters' mauling. Salla Zend and Shug Ninx mobilizes fellow smugglers nearby to rescue the Rebel strike group and escape Byss.\n\nOn New Alderaan, Leia prepares for the birth of her third child as Han and Chewie attempt to rendezvous with Lando's group. Luke's party arrives with grim news: he had reached Da Soocha to see a large missile appear and destroy the planet, with the Rebel Alliance command presumably killed. He uses the time to train the Ysanna siblings as Kam and Empatojayos practice their Jedi skills as well. Unknown to them, the Emperor's Dark Side Elites have tortured a Rebel pilot into revealing the location of New Alderaan. The Emperor sees this as an opportunity to capture the Skywalker siblings and Leia's offspring in one fell swoop. The Darksiders attempt to poison Luke, but Vima saves him as the entire settlement goes into action to fight the Imperials, who have deployed AT-ATs as backup. In the course of the fighting, Jem is killed and Rayf saves Leia's twins from being kidnapped. The Millennium Falcon and Lando's forces arrive and defeat the Imperial assault, then evacuate the New Alderaan survivors.\n\nThe Rebels relocate to the space stations of Nespis VIII, where they discover that the Alliance had evacuated Pinnacle Base before it was destroyed. On Nespis VIII, Anakin Solo is born and the Alliance plots the final destruction of the Empire.\n\n===''Empire's End''===\nAfter perishing in battle with Luke and Leia Skywalker in ''Dark Empire I'', Emperor Palpatine is forced to occupy an inferior clone body, since it was the last clone body that remained. Unknown to him, his personal physician had been corrupted by [[List of minor Star Wars characters#Jax, Carnor|Carnor Jax]], backed by a number of other high-ranking Imperial personnel. The physician had deliberately inserted genetic material and contaminants into all stored samples of the Emperor's original body, to the effect that the resulting bodies would be nowhere as resistant to the ravaging effects of the Dark Side as the original.\n\nThe last clone body not destroyed by Skywalker or traitorous Imperials is now aging rapidly, and Palpatine's final end is near, unless he can either fix his genetic material (an impossibility since no unaltered samples remain) or insert his spirit into another body. After consulting with ancient Sith Lords on the mausoleum planet [[Korriban]], Palpatine learns that [[Han Solo|Han]] and [[Princess Leia|Leia's]] youngest child, named [[Anakin Solo|Anakin]] after his deceased grandfather, has the only workable body.\n\nPalpatine follows the Solos to [[Onderon]] in order to gain a new body, to ensure the future of his rule. A fierce duel occurs between Luke Skywalker and his Jedi team and Palpatine; finally, Han Solo wrongly shoots the Emperor, allowing him to be out of his physical form and get what he wanted: Anakin's body. He desperately tries to send his spirit into the infant Anakin Solo, but he is blocked by the soul of the dying [[Jedi]], Empatojayos Brand, who makes the ultimate sacrifice in willingly sending his eternal soul into the \"madness beyond death\" that is the Dark Side, to ensure Palpatine would go as well and can never return. Luke then vows to revive the Jedi Order. After the death of Palpatine, a projectile from the Galaxy Gun is shot into Byss (since the crew were frightened by the potential collision, and also misfired), utterly destroying Byss, and destroying the second ''Eclipse''-class Star Destroyer, ''Eclipse II'', which was steered into a collision course with the Galaxy Gun by [[R2-D2]], thus ending the Empire's harsh rule.\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Audiobooks===\nIn 1994 and 1995 respectively, [[Time Warner Cable|Time Warner Audio Publishing]] released audio dramas of the first and second volumes of ''Dark Empire''. The cast was:\n* [[John Cygan]] - as [[Luke Skywalker]], [[Wedge Antilles]], Vill Goir, Okko and Umak Leth\n* [[Joe Hacker]] - as [[Han Solo]], [[Boba Fett]], [[List of Star Wars characters|Empatojayos Brand]] and Lo Khan\n* [[Ann Patricio]] - as [[Princess Leia]] and [[Mon Mothma]]\n* [[Nick Jameson]] - as [[Galactic Emperor|Emperor]] [[Palpatine]] and Governor Beltane\n* [[Jim Ward (voice actor)|Jim Ward]] - as [[C-3PO]], Kam Solusar and Executor Sedriss\n* [[Glynnis Talken]] - as Salla Zend, [[List of Star Wars characters|Vima-Da-Boda]] and [[Jem Ysanna]]\n* [[Andy Cowan]] - as [[Admiral Ackbar]], [[List of Star Wars characters|Zevulon Veers]] and Baddon Fass\n* [[Billy Dee Williams]] - as [[Lando Calrissian]]\n\nLater in 1995, a ''Dark Empire: Collector's Edition'' CD set was released that collected the 2 ''Dark Empire'' audio dramas as well as an exclusive adaptation of ''Empire's End'', the final chapter of the Dark Empire saga.\n\n=== Animation ===\nOn June 30th 2019, the YouTube channel [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCN-LbjEJ-skS17QwvCiJA8A?view_as=subscriber WilkinsAnimations] published a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNF7qrqvGtg&t=6s teaser trailer] for a short animated series based on ''Dark Empire'', making use of the comic as reference, with music composer [[imdbname:3792999|Daniel Ciurlizza]] of [https://www.outlierstudios.co/ Outlierstudios] producing the soundtrack for the non-profit fan series. The first episode of the series; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lADCO-Ar76U ''The Destiny of a Jedi''], was released October 26th 2019.\n\n==Impact==\nAlong with [[Timothy Zahn]]'s books, ''Dark Empire'' has been credited with sustaining the profitability of ''Star Wars'' during the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/how-dark-empire-kickstarted-star-wars-comics-for-a-new-generation|title=How ''Dark Empire'' kickstarted ''Star Wars'' comics for a new generation|first=Jamie|last=Greene|publisher=StarWars.com|date=2018-02-26|accessdate=2020-02-10}}</ref> By the end of the decade, it had sold over 100,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starwars.com/eu/lit/comics/f20000405/indexp2.html|title=The Dark Empire Saga|publisher=StarWars.com|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2020-02-10|archivedate=2005-04-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408013207/http://starwars.com/eu/lit/comics/f20000405/indexp2.html}}</ref>\n\n[[Kenner]] released four [[Star Wars action figures|action figures]] based on the series in 1998: Luke, Leia, Palpatine, and an Imperial sentinel; the cases for each of the figures folded out into 3-D backdrops based on the comic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luke Skywalker (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1120 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Princess Leia Organa (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1347 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Palpatine (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1343 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Imperial Sentinel (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1344 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In 2008, figures of Luke and Palpatine from ''Dark Empire II'' were released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luke Skywalker (Dark Empire II) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=96 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Palpatine (Dark Empire II) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=97 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Dark Empire'' has appeared on several top ten lists related to the [[Star Wars expanded to other media|Expanded Universe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-best-legends-stories-expanded-universe-not-canon/|title=Star Wars: 15 best stories that are no longer canon|first=Andy|last=Andersen|publisher=Screen Rant|date=2017-05-05|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/star-wars-the-force-awakens/expanded-universe-legends-best-stories/|title=Luke goes Dark: The 10 best Star Wars Expanded Universe stories|first=Tim|last=Martin|publisher=The Telegraph|date=2015-12-18|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref> In a review for Sci-Fi Block, Robert Ring called the series \"an essential Star Wars classic\" but commented that the ending was rushed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scifiblock.com/reviews/comics/star-wars-dark-empire-trilogy-hardcover-collection-review.htm|title=Star Wars: Dark Empire Trilogy|first=Robert|last=Ring|publisher=Sci-Fi Block|date=2010-09-16|accessdate=2020-02-11|archivedate=2010-09-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917140157/http://scifiblock.com/reviews/comics/star-wars-dark-empire-trilogy-hardcover-collection-review.htm}}</ref> Writing for [[Tor Books]], Ryan Britt stated that the first ''Dark Empire'' was superior to its sequels and praised it for taking stylistic departures from other works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2013/04/04/star-wars-dark-empire/|title=''Star Wars: Dark Empire'' is all about addiction|first=Ryan|last=Britt|publisher=Tor|date=2013-04-04|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2012 acquisition of Lucasfilm by [[Disney]], in April 2014, most of the licensed ''Star Wars'' novels and comics produced since [[Star Wars (film)|the originating 1977 film]] were rebranded as 'Legends' and declared non-canon to the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page |title=The Legendary ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe Turns a New Page |website=StarWars.com |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Following the release of ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' in 2019, several critics interpreted the circumstances of Palpatine's return as amounting to a tribute to ''Dark Empire''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a28916176/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-dark-empire-comics-theory-palpatine-rey-twist-spoiler/|title=Star Wars the Rise of Skywalker Palpatine twist might be spoiled in the Dark Empire comics|first=Dom|last=Nero|publisher=Esquire|date=2019-09-05|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/19/21030344/how-is-emperor-palpatine-alive-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-snoke-kylo-rey-vader-spoilers|title=Answering the biggest questions about Palpatine's return to Star Wars|first=Dave|last=Gonzales|publisher=Polygon|date=2019-12-19|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-easter-eggs-and-references.html|title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker easter eggs & references|first=Ryan|last=Britt|publisher=Vulture|date=2019-12-20|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref> The film's novelization reveals that Palpatine returned using a clone body, much like his return in the comic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bacon |first=Thomas |title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker Book Confirms Palpatine Was A Clone! |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-palpatine-clone-rise-skywalker-confirm-novel/ |website=ScreenRant |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://starwars.wikia.com/wiki/Dark_Empire ''Dark Empire''] at [[Wookieepedia]]\n* {{gcdb series|id=14507|title=''Dark Empire I''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=290|title=''Dark Empire I''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=5120|title=''Dark Empire II''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=291|title=''Dark Empire II''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=15820|title=''Empire's End''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=388|title=''Empire's End''}}\n\n{{Star Wars}}\n{{Star Wars comics}}\n\n[[Category:1994 audio plays]]\n[[Category:1994 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1995 audio plays]]\n[[Category:1995 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:Comics based on Star Wars]]\n[[Category:Comics about cloning]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the metal band|Dark Empire (band)}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox comics meta series <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title               = Dark Empire\n|image               = Darkempirei.jpg\n|imagesize           = 200\n|caption             = ''Dark Empire I'' (Trade Paperback)\n|alt                 =\n|schedule            = Monthly\n|limited             = y\n|titles              = ''[[#Dark Empire I|Dark Empire I]]''<br />''[[#Dark Empire II|Dark Empire II]]''<br />''[[#Empire's End|Empire's End]]''\n|notable             = y\n|lang                =\n|SciFi               = y\n|Adaptation          =\n|Adapt_link          =\n|publisher           = [[Dark Horse Comics]]\n|date                = '''''Dark Empire I'''''<br />December 1991&nbsp;\u2013 October 1992<br />'''''Dark Empire II'''''<br />December 1994&nbsp;\u2013 May 1995<br />'''''Empire's End'''''<br />October\u2013November 1995\n|issues              = '''''Dark Empire I''''': 6<br />'''''Dark Empire II''''': 6<br />'''''Empire's End''''': 2\n|main_char_team      =\n|writers             = [[Tom Veitch]]\n|artists             = '''''Dark Empire I''''' and '''''Dark Empire II'''''<br />[[Cam Kennedy]]<br />'''''Empire's End'''''<br />[[Jim Baikie]]\n|pencillers          =\n|inkers              =\n|letterers           =\n|colorists           =\n|editors             =\n|creative_team_month =\n|creative_team_year  =\n|creators            =\n|reprint             =\n|relang              =\n|relang#             =\n|TPB                 = Dark Empire I\n|ISBN                = 1-56971-073-2\n|TPB1                = Dark Empire Trilogy\n|ISBN1               = 1-59582-612-2\n|subcat              = Dark Horse Comics\n|altcat              =\n|alttop              =\n|sort                = Dark Empire\n|addpubcat#          =\n}}\n'''''Dark Empire''''' is a ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[comic book]] [[metaseries]] produced by [[Dark Horse Comics]]. It consists of [[#Dark Empire I|a six-issue]] [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] written by [[Tom Veitch]] and drawn by [[Cam Kennedy]], followed by [[#Dark Empire II|a second six-issue limited series]] by Veitch and Kennedy and [[#Empire's End|a two-issue limited series]] written by Veitch and drawn by [[Jim Baikie]]. The initial series is notable for being one of the very first ''Star Wars'' comics to be produced by Dark Horse Comics, who had acquired the comic rights to the ''Star Wars'' franchise in the early 1990s.\n\nPart of the [[Star Wars expanded to other media|''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe]], the trilogy follows events in the ''Star Wars'' franchise six years after ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Comics Companion|last1=Windham|first1=Ryder|authorlink1=Ryder Windham|last2=Wallace|first2=Daniel|editor1-last=Allie|editor1-first=Scott|editor1-link=Scott Allie|editor2-last=Simpson|editor2-first=Robert|year=2006|publisher=[[Dark Horse Comics]]}}</ref> specifically the aftereffects of [[Timothy Zahn]]'s [[Thrawn trilogy|''Thrawn'' trilogy]]. The story deals with the return of the villainous [[Palpatine]], having successfully cheated death by having his spiritual entity \"reincarnated\" through the essence transfer ritual and cloning technology. Other themes include [[Luke Skywalker]] temporarily succumbing to the dark side of [[the Force]], the official return of [[Boba Fett]] (who had seemingly died after being swallowed by the [[Sarlacc]] in ''Return of the Jedi''), and the first appearance of [[Princess Leia]] and [[Han Solo]]'s son [[Anakin Solo]].\n\n==Publication history==\nThe ''Dark Empire I'' story was originally developed by [[Tom Veitch]] and [[Cam Kennedy]] for [[Marvel Comics]]. Veitch and Kennedy were approached by [[Lucasfilm]] based on their success with ''[[The Light and Darkness War]]''.<ref>''The [[Dark Empire Sourcebook]]'', [[West End Games]], 1st edition, 1993. Horne, Michael, {{ISBN|0-87431-194-2}}</ref><ref>''The Dark Side Sourcebook'', [[Wizards of the Coast]], 1st printing, 2001. Bill Slavicsek, J. D. Wiker, {{ISBN|0-7869-1849-7}}</ref> After difficulties with Marvel, the project was picked up by Dark Horse Comics.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-131/|title= Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #131|first= Brian|last= Cronin|date= November 29, 2007|publisher= Comic Book Resources|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150426232903/http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/11/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-131|archivedate= April 26, 2015|url-status=live|quote=  }}</ref>\n\n''Dark Empire I'' was a six-issue limited series published bimonthly in [[1991 in comics|1991]] and [[1992 in comics|1992]], ''Dark Empire II'' was also a six-issue limited series published from [[1994 in comics|1994]] to [[1995 in comics|1995]] and ''Empire's End'', two-issue limited series published in 1995. All three series, plus a sourcebook, would be combined in a hardbound omnibus in 2010.\n\nThe individual comic issues each feature several bonus pages of written context; ''Dark Empire'' for instance details some of Palpatine's history related to his return, including excerpts of books written from his perspective.\n\nThe various series have been collected into [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperbacks]]:\n* ''Dark Empire'' (1993, {{ISBN|1-56971-073-2}})\n* ''Dark Empire II'' (1995, {{ISBN|1-56971-119-4}})\n* ''Empire's End'' (1997, {{ISBN|1-56971-306-5}})\n\nThe entire series has also been collected into a single hardcover:\n* ''Dark Empire Trilogy'' (352 pages, Dark Horse Comics, September 2010, {{ISBN|1-59582-612-2}}, [[Titan Books]], December 2010, {{ISBN|1-84856-887-8}})\n\n==Plot==\n\n===''Dark Empire''===\nSeveral years after the events of ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'', the ''[[Millennium Falcon]]'' leads a Rebel task force to [[Coruscant]]. Han Solo, Leia Organa, [[Chewbacca]] and [[C-3PO]] are heading to the planet to rescue [[Luke Skywalker]], R2-D2 and [[Lando Calrissian]], who have spent the past several days holding out against Imperial attacks after an earlier raid using the captured [[Star Destroyer]] ''Liberator'' goes awry and the warship crashes. The Rebels successfully rescue the survivors, but a massive energy storm appears. Luke sees the storm as a large disturbance in [[the Force]], and asks everybody to leave him behind; he lets himself be devoured by the storm.\n\nThe taskforce returns to the Rebel fleet in the Da Soocha system. Rebel commanders discuss the appearance of the Imperials coming out of the Deep Core and discover that Admiral Ackbar's homeworld of Mon Calamari is now under attack by a fleet of Imperial war machines. Called the World Devastators, the machines are designed to convert everything in their path into raw materials for building more war machines on the spot. Lando leads another taskforce with a second captured Star Destroyer leading the charge to aid in Mon Calamari's defense.\n\nMeanwhile, Luke awakes from the light of the Force storm and finds out he is aboard an old Imperial prison ship heading to [[Byss]]. The ship docks and Luke is closely escorted to a chamber, where he is stunned to see [[Emperor Palpatine]] alive. The Emperor explains that he has revived himself in a clone body and makes Luke doubt any attempt to kill him knowing he will quickly manifest in another clone. Sensing the futility and seeing the horror of what is happening in Mon Calamari, Luke humbly surrenders to becoming the Emperor's new apprentice.\n\nLeia has visions of Luke being corrupted into the Dark Side and wants to travel to Byss and save him. She and Han travel to [[Nar Shaddaa]] and try to arrange a ship to bring them past Byss' security network. Han reunites with smuggler friends Shug Ninx, Salla Zend, and Mako Spince to make it happen. Along the way, an old woman named Vima-da-Boda\u2014a former Jedi who survived the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Empire]]'s crackdown\u2014feels Leia's Force energy and gives her an old Jedi artifact. However, the Hutts have put a large bounty on Han and Leia, with Spince selling him out to [[Boba Fett]] (revealed to have survived being devoured by the Sarlacc during the events of ''Return of the Jedi''); the two escape Nar Shaddaa aboard Salla's ship, the Starlight Intruder, with the Falcon attached. The Intruder has the proper codes to get inside Byss, and Imperial security lets them in (but lock out a pursuing Fett). Han Leia, Chewie, and the droids are brought before Luke and the Emperor.\n\nLeia discovers that he holds hostage an even greater treasure: a mysterious and intelligent artifact called the [[Jedi]] [[Holocron]], a holographic cube that contains historical information about the Jedi. When Leia discovers that the Emperor is interested in possessing her third child, she steals the Holocron and the group successfully breaks out of Byss while having to leave behind Luke again. Luke faces the already frail Emperor and destroys his clone tanks, but the Emperor possesses one living clone and subdues him to his will.\n\nHan's group travels to Mon Calamari as Rebel commando forces lay siege to the World Devastators, which have been shut down by a special master code Luke was able to steal and give to R2 and C3PO for transmission to the machines. The Imperials aboard the machines still have the factories running and attack the Rebels. R2 rigs the World Devastators to destroy each other.\n\nAs the Rebels celebrate on Mon Calamari, Alliance command determines that the World Devastators are part of a larger Imperial offensive to conquer the galaxy. Leia studies the Holocron and sees an old prophecy about a pregnant woman coming to save the Jedi from doom. At the same time, a small Imperial fleet, led by the massive flagship ''Eclipse'', appears above Da Soocha. The Emperor demands that the Alliance surrender Leia to him and Luke. Leia travels on her own and appeals to Luke to break away from the Emperor. Palpatine creates a large Force storm to destroy the Rebel fleet, but Leia and Luke work together to amplify the storm beyond the Emperor's power and turn it against him. The siblings escape the doomed warship, and as Luke sees the last remnants of the Eclipse being vaporized, he declares the Jedi Knights will rise again.\n\n===''Dark Empire II''===\nWith Emperor Palpatine apparently perishing aboard the Eclipse, more worlds defy Imperial edicts, especially those that have been recently reconquered. One of these is the arms manufacturing planet Balmorra, whose planetary governor, Beltane, has begun supplying the Rebels with the latest military vehicles, such as the Viper X1 Automadon, a war droid designed to convert energy from enemy laser fire into power for its own turbolaser cannons. The Emperor's Dark Side Executor Sedriss leads a force to subdue the planet, but Beltane's troops hold the line and Sedriss is compelled to negotiate a supply agreement with him. Sedriss returns to Byss, where he kills two Dark Side Adepts who've been killing other clones of Emperor Palpatine that Luke missed. Palpatine possesses one clone to Sedriss' surprise and orders the Imperial offensive to continue.\n\nHaving pledged to reestablish the Jedi Order by finding any surviving Jedi in the galaxy, Luke Skywalker returns to Pinnacle Base on the moon Da Soocha V (orbiting Da Soocha in the Cyax System of Hutt Space of the Outer Rim) with Kam Solusar, a former Dark Jedi. Beltane tips the [[Rebel Alliance]] of a shipment of new Vipers bound for the Empire's Deep Core stronghold of Byss, and Alliance commanders accept Wedge Antilles' suggestion of intercepting the shipment for a surgical strike using the droids, with Rebel commandos in the attack. Although Luke presses for liberating more worlds to provide more staging areas for an all-out strike on Byss, Mon Mothma asks him to concentrate on rebuilding the Jedi Order instead. The Jedi Holocron educates Luke about the planet Ossus, a former Jedi-populated world destroyed by the Sith thousands of years earlier.\n\nHan, Leia and Chewie fly back to Nar Shaddaa to find Vima-da-Boda, at least where Leia last saw her. However, Vima has disappeared and every bounty hunter on the moon is still out for them, including Boba Fett, as well as an Imperial force led by two Dark Side Elites. Leia successfully fetches Vima after flying into the deeper reaches of Nar Shaddaa. Aboard Nar Shaddaa's traffic control tower, Mako Spince sees Han and guides an Imperial Star Destroyer's tractor beam on him. Han turns the tables by flying close to the tower, forcing the tractor beam to lock onto the structure and pull it instead at full power. The tower impales the Star Destroyer and it crashes into Nar Shaddaa. Fett, back in his old ship Slave I, chases the Millennium Falcon into a nearby acidic gas cloud. Han takes the risk and flies into the cloud, surprisingly appearing on the other side and stumbling onto the long-lost world of Ganath. Ganathan engineers repair the Falcon and equip it with a lightning cannon while the team meets Ganath's ruler, Empatojayos Brand, a veteran Jedi who survived the Empire's Jedi Purge. Inspired by the possibility of a Jedi rebirth, Brand joins Han's party while leaving Ganath in the hands of a military officer. Han takes out Fett and heads to a secret hideout on New Alderaan, where Han and Leia's twin children are under care.\n\nLuke and Kam fly to Ossus and chances upon the Ysanna, a warrior tribe which has rudimentary Force powers. They fight off the Ysanna attacks and sensing they are indeed Jedi, the Ysanna chief welcomes them. Having known about the trip, the Emperor orders Sedriss and fellow Dark Side Elite Vill Goir to capture them. Solusar kills Goir, but Sedriss takes one of the Ysanna hostage and leans against a tree. To everybody's surprise, the tree is a millennia-old Neti Jedi Master named Ood Bnar, who wraps Sedriss in a fatal embrace and they die in an explosion of Force energy. Bnar's heroic sacrifice leaves a part of him in the soil and a hole underneath his location reveals an old cache of lightsabers; Luke successfully discovers an old Jedi library. Two Ysanna tribe members, siblings Ralf and Jem, join Luke and Kam in leaving the planet with their elders' blessing.\n\nLando leads the Rebel infiltration into Byss and start the attack when the Viper droids are offloaded. The droids prove superior to existing Imperial defenses until the Emperor releases an army of Dark Side-mutated monsters on the attackers. The Vipers, which are attuned against energy attacks, are cut to shreds under the monsters' mauling. Salla Zend and Shug Ninx mobilizes fellow smugglers nearby to rescue the Rebel strike group and escape Byss.\n\nOn New Alderaan, Leia prepares for the birth of her third child as Han and Chewie attempt to rendezvous with Lando's group. Luke's party arrives with grim news: he had reached Da Soocha to see a large missile appear and destroy the planet, with the Rebel Alliance command presumably killed. He uses the time to train the Ysanna siblings as Kam and Empatojayos practice their Jedi skills as well. Unknown to them, the Emperor's Dark Side Elites have tortured a Rebel pilot into revealing the location of New Alderaan. The Emperor sees this as an opportunity to capture the Skywalker siblings and Leia's offspring in one fell swoop. The Darksiders attempt to poison Luke, but Vima saves him as the entire settlement goes into action to fight the Imperials, who have deployed AT-ATs as backup. In the course of the fighting, Jem is killed and Rayf saves Leia's twins from being kidnapped. The Millennium Falcon and Lando's forces arrive and defeat the Imperial assault, then evacuate the New Alderaan survivors.\n\nThe Rebels relocate to the space stations of Nespis VIII, where they discover that the Alliance had evacuated Pinnacle Base before it was destroyed. On Nespis VIII, Anakin Solo is born and the Alliance plots the final destruction of the Empire.\n\n===''Empire's End''===\nAfter perishing in battle with Luke and Leia Skywalker in ''Dark Empire I'', Emperor Palpatine is forced to occupy an inferior clone body, since it was the last clone body that remained. Unknown to him, his personal physician had been corrupted by [[List of minor Star Wars characters#Jax, Carnor|Carnor Jax]], backed by a number of other high-ranking Imperial personnel. The physician had deliberately inserted genetic material and contaminants into all stored samples of the Emperor's original body, to the effect that the resulting bodies would be nowhere as resistant to the ravaging effects of the Dark Side as the original.\n\nThe last clone body not destroyed by Skywalker or traitorous Imperials is now aging rapidly, and Palpatine's final end is near, unless he can either fix his genetic material (an impossibility since no unaltered samples remain) or insert his spirit into another body. After consulting with ancient Sith Lords on the mausoleum planet [[Korriban]], Palpatine learns that [[Han Solo|Han]] and [[Princess Leia|Leia's]] youngest child, named [[Anakin Solo|Anakin]] after his deceased grandfather, has the only workable body.\n\nPalpatine follows the Solos to [[Onderon]] in order to gain a new body, to ensure the future of his rule. A fierce duel occurs between Luke Skywalker and his Jedi team and Palpatine; finally, Han Solo wrongly shoots the Emperor, allowing him to be out of his physical form and get what he wanted: Anakin's body. He desperately tries to send his spirit into the infant Anakin Solo, but he is blocked by the soul of the dying [[Jedi]], Empatojayos Brand, who makes the ultimate sacrifice in willingly sending his eternal soul into the \"madness beyond death\" that is the Dark Side, to ensure Palpatine would go as well and can never return. Luke then vows to revive the Jedi Order. After the death of Palpatine, a projectile from the Galaxy Gun is shot into Byss (since the crew were frightened by the potential collision, and also misfired), utterly destroying Byss, and destroying the second ''Eclipse''-class Star Destroyer, ''Eclipse II'', which was steered into a collision course with the Galaxy Gun by [[R2-D2]], thus ending the Empire's harsh rule.\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Audiobooks===\nIn 1994 and 1995 respectively, [[Time Warner Cable|Time Warner Audio Publishing]] released audio dramas of the first and second volumes of ''Dark Empire''. The cast was:\n* [[John Cygan]] - as [[Luke Skywalker]], [[Wedge Antilles]], Vill Goir, Okko and Umak Leth\n* [[Joe Hacker]] - as [[Han Solo]], [[Boba Fett]], [[List of Star Wars characters|Empatojayos Brand]] and Lo Khan\n* [[Ann Patricio]] - as [[Princess Leia]] and [[Mon Mothma]]\n* [[Nick Jameson]] - as [[Galactic Emperor|Emperor]] [[Palpatine]] and Governor Beltane\n* [[Jim Ward (voice actor)|Jim Ward]] - as [[C-3PO]], Kam Solusar and Executor Sedriss\n* [[Glynnis Talken]] - as Salla Zend, [[List of Star Wars characters|Vima-Da-Boda]] and [[Jem Ysanna]]\n* [[Andy Cowan]] - as [[Admiral Ackbar]], [[List of Star Wars characters|Zevulon Veers]] and Baddon Fass\n* [[Billy Dee Williams]] - as [[Lando Calrissian]]\n\nLater in 1995, a ''Dark Empire: Collector's Edition'' CD set was released that collected the 2 ''Dark Empire'' audio dramas as well as an exclusive adaptation of ''Empire's End'', the final chapter of the Dark Empire saga.\n\n=== Animation ===\nOn June 30th 2019, the YouTube channel [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCN-LbjEJ-skS17QwvCiJA8A?view_as=subscriber WilkinsAnimations] published a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNF7qrqvGtg&t=6s teaser trailer] for a short animated series based on ''Dark Empire'', making use of the comic as reference, with music composer [[imdbname:3792999|Daniel Ciurlizza]] of [https://www.outlierstudios.co/ Outlierstudios] producing the soundtrack for the non-profit fan series. The first episode of the series; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lADCO-Ar76U ''The Destiny of a Jedi''], was released October 26th 2019.\n\n==Impact==\nAlong with [[Timothy Zahn]]'s books, ''Dark Empire'' has been credited with sustaining the profitability of ''Star Wars'' during the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/how-dark-empire-kickstarted-star-wars-comics-for-a-new-generation|title=How ''Dark Empire'' kickstarted ''Star Wars'' comics for a new generation|first=Jamie|last=Greene|publisher=StarWars.com|date=2018-02-26|accessdate=2020-02-10}}</ref> By the end of the decade, it had sold over 100,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starwars.com/eu/lit/comics/f20000405/indexp2.html|title=The Dark Empire Saga|publisher=StarWars.com|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2020-02-10|archivedate=2005-04-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408013207/http://starwars.com/eu/lit/comics/f20000405/indexp2.html}}</ref>\n\n[[Kenner]] released four [[Star Wars action figures|action figures]] based on the series in 1998: Luke, Leia, Palpatine, and an Imperial sentinel; the cases for each of the figures folded out into 3-D backdrops based on the comic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luke Skywalker (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1120 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Princess Leia Organa (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1347 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Palpatine (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1343 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Imperial Sentinel (The Power Of The Force) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=1344 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In 2008, figures of Luke and Palpatine from ''Dark Empire II'' were released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luke Skywalker (Dark Empire II) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=96 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Palpatine (Dark Empire II) |url=https://jedibusiness.com/figureDetails.aspx?id=97 |website=Jedi Business |accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Dark Empire'' has appeared on several top ten lists related to the [[Star Wars expanded to other media|Expanded Universe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-best-legends-stories-expanded-universe-not-canon/|title=Star Wars: 15 best stories that are no longer canon|first=Andy|last=Andersen|publisher=Screen Rant|date=2017-05-05|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/star-wars-the-force-awakens/expanded-universe-legends-best-stories/|title=Luke goes Dark: The 10 best Star Wars Expanded Universe stories|first=Tim|last=Martin|publisher=The Telegraph|date=2015-12-18|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref> In a review for Sci-Fi Block, Robert Ring called the series \"an essential Star Wars classic\" but commented that the ending was rushed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scifiblock.com/reviews/comics/star-wars-dark-empire-trilogy-hardcover-collection-review.htm|title=Star Wars: Dark Empire Trilogy|first=Robert|last=Ring|publisher=Sci-Fi Block|date=2010-09-16|accessdate=2020-02-11|archivedate=2010-09-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917140157/http://scifiblock.com/reviews/comics/star-wars-dark-empire-trilogy-hardcover-collection-review.htm}}</ref> Writing for [[Tor Books]], Ryan Britt stated that the first ''Dark Empire'' was superior to its sequels and praised it for taking stylistic departures from other works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2013/04/04/star-wars-dark-empire/|title=''Star Wars: Dark Empire'' is all about addiction|first=Ryan|last=Britt|publisher=Tor|date=2013-04-04|accessdate=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2012 acquisition of Lucasfilm by [[Disney]], in April 2014, most of the licensed ''Star Wars'' novels and comics produced since [[Star Wars (film)|the originating 1977 film]] were rebranded as 'Legends' and declared non-canon to the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page |title=The Legendary ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe Turns a New Page |website=StarWars.com |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Following the release of ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' in 2019, several critics interpreted the circumstances of Palpatine's return as amounting to a tribute to ''Dark Empire''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a28916176/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-dark-empire-comics-theory-palpatine-rey-twist-spoiler/|title=Star Wars the Rise of Skywalker Palpatine twist might be spoiled in the Dark Empire comics|first=Dom|last=Nero|publisher=Esquire|date=2019-09-05|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/19/21030344/how-is-emperor-palpatine-alive-in-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-snoke-kylo-rey-vader-spoilers|title=Answering the biggest questions about Palpatine's return to Star Wars|first=Dave|last=Gonzales|publisher=Polygon|date=2019-12-19|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-easter-eggs-and-references.html|title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker easter eggs & references|first=Ryan|last=Britt|publisher=Vulture|date=2019-12-20|accessdate=2020-01-26}}</ref> The film's novelization reveals that Palpatine returned using a clone body, much like his return in the comic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bacon |first=Thomas |title=Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker Book Confirms Palpatine Was A Clone! |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-palpatine-clone-rise-skywalker-confirm-novel/ |website=ScreenRant |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://starwars.wikia.com/wiki/Dark_Empire ''Dark Empire''] at [[Wookieepedia]]\n* {{gcdb series|id=14507|title=''Dark Empire I''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=290|title=''Dark Empire I''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=5120|title=''Dark Empire II''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=291|title=''Dark Empire II''}}\n* {{gcdb series|id=15820|title=''Empire's End''}}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=title|id=388|title=''Empire's End''}}\n\n{{Star Wars}}\n{{Star Wars comics}}\n\n[[Category:1994 audio plays]]\n[[Category:1994 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1995 audio plays]]\n[[Category:1995 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:Comics based on Star Wars]]\n[[Category:Comics about cloning]]\n", "name_user": "Maxcardun", "label": "safe", "comment": "Yeesh it wasn't a police sting.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Empire"}
{"title_page": "Lorenzo Ricci (athlete)", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T11|100 metres - T11]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4x100 metre relay T13|4x100 metre relay - T13]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Lorenzo Ricci''' (born 13 May 1971 in [[Sarzana]]) is a [[Paralympic]] [[track and field|athlete]] from [[Italy]] competing mainly in [[T11 (classification)|category T11]] sprint events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coni.it/it/attivita-istituzionali/onorificenze/home/scheda-persona/schedaatleta.html?cognome=RICCI&nome=LORENZO&id=121719 |title=Lorenzo Ricci |website=CONI.it |language=it |publisher=[[Comitato Olimpico Nazionale Italiano]] |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nLorenzo competed in the 100m and 200m at both the [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000]] and [[2004 Summer Paralympics]] winning a gold medal in the T11 100m in 2000.  He also won a gold as part of the Italian 4 \u00d7 100 m for T13 in 2004.<ref>[http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?sport=all&games=all&Medal=all&npc=all&name=Ricci&fname=Lorenzo&gender=all profile on paralympic.org]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=lorenzo-ricci|old_id=870182}}\n* {{World Athletics|172388}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ricci, Lorenzo}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n\n{{Italy-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ITA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T11|100 metres - T11]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4x100 metre relay T13|4x100 metre relay - T13]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Lorenzo Ricci''' is a [[paralympic]] [[track and field|athlete]] from [[Italy]] competing mainly in category T11 sprint events.\n\nLorenzo competed in the 100m and 200m at both the [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000]] and [[2004 Summer Paralympics]] winning a gold medal in the T11 100m in 2000.  He also won a gold as part of the Italian 4 \u00d7 100 m for T13 in 2004.<ref>[http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?sport=all&games=all&Medal=all&npc=all&name=Ricci&fname=Lorenzo&gender=all profile on paralympic.org]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|870182}}\n* {{IAAF|172388}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ricci, Lorenzo}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Italy]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Italy-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorenzo_Ricci_(athlete)"}
{"title_page": "Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow", "text_new": "{{Other people5|Sophie of Mecklenburg (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|consort=yes\n| name            = Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow\n| image           = Sophiemecklenburgdenmark.jpg\n| caption         = Portrait by [[Hans Knieper]], [[Circa|c.]]&nbsp;1572<br/>[[Rosenborg Castle]], [[Copenhagen]]\n| succession      = [[List of Danish consorts|Queen consort of Denmark]] and [[List of Norwegian consorts|Norway]]\n| reign           = 1572\u20131588\n| spouse          = [[Frederick II of Denmark]]\n| issue           = [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Brunswick|Elizabeth, Duchess of Brunswick]]<br> [[Anne of Denmark|Anne, Queen of England and Scotland]] <br>[[Christian IV of Denmark]] <br>[[Ulrik of Denmark (1578\u20131624)|Ulrich II, Prince-Bishop of Schwerin]]<br>[[Augusta of Denmark|Augusta, Duchess Holstein-Gottorp]]<br>[[Hedwig of Denmark|Hedwig, Electress of Saxony]]<br> [[John, Prince of Schleswig-Holstein]] \n| house           = [[House of Mecklenburg-Schwerin|Mecklenburg-Schwerin]]\n| titles          =\n| father          = [[Ulrich III of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]]\n| mother          = [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n| birth_date   = 4 September 1557\n| birth_place  = [[Wismar]]\n| date of christening  =\n| place of christening =\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1631|10|14|1557|9|4|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Nyk\u00f6ping]]\n| burial_place  = [[Roskilde Cathedral]]\n| religion    = [[Lutheranism]]\n|}}\n'''Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow''' (4 September 1557 \u2013 14 October 1631) was Queen of Denmark and Norway by marriage to [[Frederick II of Denmark]]. She was the mother of King [[Christian IV of Denmark]]. She was Regent of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] 1590\u20131594.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\">[http://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/1348/origin/170/  Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Wismar]], she was the daughter of Duke [[Ulrich III of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] and Princess [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]] (a daughter of [[Frederick I of Denmark|Frederick I]] and [[Sophie of Pomerania]]). Through her father, a grandson of [[Elizabeth of Denmark (1485\u20131555)|Elizabeth of Oldenburg]], she descended from King [[John of Denmark]]. Like Ulrich, she had a great love of knowledge. Later, she would be known as one of the most learned Queens of the time.\n\n==Queen==\nAt the age of fourteen Sophie, on 20 July 1572, married [[Frederick II of Denmark]] in [[Copenhagen]]; he was thirty-eight. They were first half-cousins, through their grandfather, Frederick I, King of Denmark and Norway. They met at Nyk\u00f8bing Castle, when it had been arranged for the king to meet with Margaret of Pomerania. She was brought to Denmark by Sophie's parents, who decided to also bring their own daughter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Grinder-Hansen|first=Poul|title=Frederik II - Danmarks Ren\u00e6ssancekonge|publisher=Gyldendal|year=2013|isbn=978-87-02-13569-5|location=|pages=See Chapter 12, K\u00e6rlighed, chapter 24, Private notater.}}</ref>. Sophie found favour with the king, who betrothed himself to her, and married her six months later.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skaarup|first=Bi|date=1994|title=Soffye|url=https://www.skalk.dk/tidsskriftet/arkiv/|journal=Skalk - Nyt fra fortiden|volume=5|pages=|via=Skalk.dk}}</ref> \nKing Frederick had been in love with the noblewoman Anne Corfitzdatter Hardenberg for many years, but was unable to marry her due to her being a noblewoman, not a princess, the opposition of the Danish Privy Council as well as eventually Anne herself. <ref name=\":0\" />\n \nDespite the age difference between Sophie and Frederick, the marriage was described as harmonious. Queen Sophie was a loving mother, nursing her children personally during their illnesses. King Frederick was well-known for beign fond of drinking and hunting<ref name=\":0\" />, but he was a loving spouse to Sophie, writing off her with great fondness in his personal diary (where he kept careful track of where she and their children were in the country<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Otto|first=Car\u00f8e|date=01-01-1873|title=Kong Frederik II's Kalenderoptegnelser for Aarene 1583, 1584 og 1587|url=https://tidsskrift.dk/historisktidsskrift/article/view/54223/72899|journal=Historisk Tidsskrift|volume=4 r\u00e6kke, 3 bind|pages=|via=Historisk Tidsskrift}}</ref>) and there is no evidence of extramarital affairs on the part of either spouse. <ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\" /> Their marriage is described as having been harmonious. <ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> All of their children were sent to live with her parents in Mecklenburg for the first years of their lives, with the possible exception of the last son, Hans, as it was the belief at the time that the parents would indulge their children too much.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She showed a keen interest in science and visited the astronomer [[Tycho Brahe]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She was also interested in the old songs of [[folklore]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/>\n\nShe proved a diligent matchmaker. Her daughter, [[Anne of Denmark]], would marry [[James VI of Scotland]] and become queen consort in 1589. She arranged the marriage against the will of the Council.\n\n==Regency==\nQueen Sophie had no political power during the lifetime of her spouse.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> When her underage son [[Christian IV]] became king in 1588, she was given no place in the regency council in Denmark itself.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> From 1590, however, she acted as regent for the duchies of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] for her son.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/>\n\nShe organised a grand funeral for her spouse, arranged for the dowries for her daughters and for her own allowance, all independently and against the will of the council.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She engaged in a power struggle with the regents of Denmark and with the Council of State, which had Christian declared of age in 1593.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She wished the duchies to be divided between her younger sons, which caused a conflict.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> Sophie only gave up her position the following year, 1594. As such, she came into conflict with the government, which exiled her to the Palace of [[Nyk\u00f6ping Castle|Nyk\u00f8bing Slot]] on the island of [[Falster]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She spent her time there in the study of [[chemistry]], [[astronomy]] and other sciences.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She also renovated Nyk\u00f8bing Slot.\n\n==Later life==\nThe Dowager Queen Sophie managed her estates in [[Lolland]]-Falster so well that her son could borrow money from her on several occasions for his wars.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She also engaged in large-scale trade and in money-lending.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She often visited Mecklenburg, and attended her daughter's wedding in [[Dresden]] in 1602. In 1603 she became involved in an inheritance dispute with her uncle, which remained unsolved at his death in 1610.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> In 1608, she managed to soften the punishment of [[Rigborg Brockenhuus]], and in 1628, she was one of the influential people who prevented her son from having her grandson's lover, [[Anne Lykke]], accused of [[witchcraft]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> Sophie died in [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster]] at the age of seventy-four as the richest woman in Northern Europe.\n\n==Issue==\n#  [[Elisabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Braunshweig|Elizabeth]] (25 August 1573 \u2013 19 June 1626), married in 1590 to [[Henry Julius, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]].\n# [[Anne of Denmark|Anne]] (12 December 1574 \u2013 2 March 1619), married on 23 November 1589 to King [[James I of England|James VI of Scotland (later James I of England)]]\n# [[Christian IV of Denmark and Norway]] (12 April 1577 \u2013 28 February 1648)\n# [[Ulrik of Denmark (1578\u20131624)|Ulrik]] (30 December 1578 \u2013 27 March 1624 in [[R\u00fchn]]), last [[Bishop of Schleswig|Bishop of the old Schleswig see]] (1602\u20131624), and as Ulrich II [[Diocesan administrator#Administrators of prince-bishoprics|Lutheran Administrator]] of the [[Bishopric of Schwerin|Prince-Bishopric of Schwerin]] (1603\u20131624), married with Lady Catherine [[von Hahn|Hahn]]-Hinrichshagen\n# John August (1579\u20131579), died in infancy\n# [[Augusta of Denmark|Augusta]] (8 April 1580 \u2013 5 February 1639), married on 30 August 1596 to Duke [[Johann Adolf of Holstein-Gottorp]]\n# [[Hedwig of Denmark|Hedwig]] (5 August 1581 \u2013 26 November 1641), married on 12 September 1602 to [[Christian II, Elector of Saxony]]\n# [[John, Prince of Schleswig-Holstein]] (9 July 1583 \u2013 28 October 1602)\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{see also|Mecklenburg Ancestral Table}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow'''\n|2= 2. [[Ulrich III, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|3= 3. [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n|4= 4. [[Albrecht VII, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|5= 5. [[Anna of Brandenburg, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Anna of Brandenburg]]\n|6= 6. [[Frederick I of Denmark]]\n|7= 7. [[Sophie of Pomerania]]\n|8= 8. [[Magnus II, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|9= 9. [[Sophie of Pomerania-Stettin|Sophie of Pomerania]]\n|10= 10. [[Joachim I Nestor, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n|11= 11. [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Electress of Brandenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n|12= 12. [[Christian I of Denmark]]\n|13= 13. [[Dorothea of Brandenburg]]\n|14= 14. [[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania]]\n|15= 15. [[Anna Jagiellon, Duchess of Pomerania|Anna Jagiellon]]\n|16= 16. [[Henry IV, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|17= 17. [[Dorothea of Brandenburg, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Dorothea of Brandenburg]]\n|18= 18. [[Eric II, Duke of Pomerania]] (=#28)\n|19= 19. [[Sophia of Pomerania-Stolp]] (=#29)\n|20= 20. [[John Cicero, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n|21= 21. [[Margaret of Thuringia]]\n|22= 22. [[John of Denmark]]\n|23= 23. [[Christina of Saxony]]\n|24= 24. [[Dietrich, Count of Oldenburg]]\n|25= 25. [[Helvig of Schauenburg]]\n|26= 26. [[John, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach]]\n|27= 27. [[Barbara of Saxe-Wittenberg]]\n|28= 28. [[Eric II, Duke of Pomerania]] (=#18)\n|29= 29. [[Sophia of Pomerania-Stolp]] (=#19)\n|30= 30. [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]]\n|31= 31. [[Elizabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elizabeth of Austria]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow, Queen of Denmark}}\n* [http://www.kongernessamling.dk/en/rosenborg/person/sophie/ Queen Sophie] at the website of the [[Royal Danish Collection]]\n*http://www.guide2womenleaders.com/womeninpower/Womeninpower1570.htm\n*http://www.thepeerage.com/p10139.htm\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Mecklenburg-Schwerin]]|4 September|1557|14 October|1631|[[House of Mecklenburg]]}}\n{{S-roy|dk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Dorothea of Saxe-Lauenburg]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Danish consorts|Queen consort of Denmark]] and [[List of Norwegian consorts|Norway]]|years=1572\u20131588}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Anne Catherine of Brandenburg]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Danish consorts}}\n{{Norwegian consorts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sophie Of Mecklenburg-Gustrow}}\n[[Category:1557 births]]\n[[Category:1631 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Danish people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Norwegian people]]\n[[Category:16th-century women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Danish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Norwegian people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Roskilde Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Danish royal consorts]]\n[[Category:House of Mecklenburg-Schwerin]]\n[[Category:Norwegian royal consorts]]\n[[Category:People from Wismar]]\n[[Category:16th-century women rulers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people5|Sophie of Mecklenburg (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|consort=yes\n| name            = Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow\n| image           = Sophiemecklenburgdenmark.jpg\n| caption         = Portrait by [[Hans Knieper]], [[Circa|c.]]&nbsp;1572<br/>[[Rosenborg Castle]], [[Copenhagen]]\n| succession      = [[List of Danish consorts|Queen consort of Denmark]] and [[List of Norwegian consorts|Norway]]\n| reign           = 1572\u20131588\n| spouse          = [[Frederick II of Denmark]]\n| issue           = [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Brunswick|Elizabeth, Duchess of Brunswick]]<br> [[Anne of Denmark|Anne, Queen of England and Scotland]] <br>[[Christian IV of Denmark]] <br>[[Ulrik of Denmark (1578\u20131624)|Ulrich II, Prince-Bishop of Schwerin]]<br>[[Augusta of Denmark|Augusta, Duchess Holstein-Gottorp]]<br>[[Hedwig of Denmark|Hedwig, Electress of Saxony]]<br> [[John, Prince of Schleswig-Holstein]] \n| house           = [[House of Mecklenburg-Schwerin|Mecklenburg-Schwerin]]\n| titles          =\n| father          = [[Ulrich III of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]]\n| mother          = [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n| birth_date   = 4 September 1557\n| birth_place  = [[Wismar]]\n| date of christening  =\n| place of christening =\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1631|10|14|1557|9|4|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Nyk\u00f6ping]]\n| burial_place  = [[Roskilde Cathedral]]\n| religion    = [[Lutheranism]]\n|}}\n'''Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow''' (4 September 1557 \u2013 14 October 1631) was Queen of Denmark and Norway by marriage to [[Frederick II of Denmark]]. She was the mother of King [[Christian IV of Denmark]]. She was Regent of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] 1590\u20131594.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\">[http://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/1348/origin/170/  Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Wismar]], she was the daughter of Duke [[Ulrich III of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow]] and Princess [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]] (a daughter of [[Frederick I of Denmark|Frederick I]] and [[Sophie of Pomerania]]). Through her father, a grandson of [[Elizabeth of Denmark (1485\u20131555)|Elizabeth of Oldenburg]], she descended from King [[John of Denmark]]. Like Ulrich, she had a great love of knowledge. Later, she would be known as one of the most learned Queens of the time.\n\n==Queen==\nAt the age of fourteen Sophie, on 20 July 1572, married [[Frederick II of Denmark]] in [[Copenhagen]]; he was thirty-eight. They were first half-cousins, through their grandfather, Frederick I, King of Denmark and Norway. They met at Nyk\u00f8bing Castle, when it had been arranged for the king to meet with Margaret of Pomerania. She was brought to Denmark by Sophie's parents, who brought along their own daughter in their retinue<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Grinder-Hansen|first=Poul|title=Frederik II - Danmarks Ren\u00e6ssancekonge|publisher=Gyldendal|year=2013|isbn=978-87-02-13569-5|location=|pages=See Chapter 12, K\u00e6rlighed, chapter 24, Private notater.}}</ref>. She found favour with the king, who betrothed himself to her and married her six months later.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Skaarup|first=Bi|date=1994|title=Soffye|url=https://www.skalk.dk/tidsskriftet/arkiv/|journal=Skalk - Nyt fra fortiden|volume=5|pages=|via=Skalk.dk}}</ref> \nKing Frederick had been in love with the noblewoman Anne Corfitzdatter Hardenberg for many years, but was unable to marry her due to her being a noblewoman, not a princess, the opposition of the Danish Privy Council as well as eventually Anne herself. <ref name=\":0\" />\n \nDespite the age difference between Sophie and Frederick, the marriage was described as harmonious. Queen Sophie was a loving mother, nursing her children personally during their illnesses. King Frederick was well-known for beign fond of drinking and hunting<ref name=\":0\" />, but he was a loving spouse to Sophie, writing off her with great fondness in his personal diary (where he kept careful track of where she and their children were in the country<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Otto|first=Car\u00f8e|date=01-01-1873|title=Kong Frederik II's Kalenderoptegnelser for Aarene 1583, 1584 og 1587|url=https://tidsskrift.dk/historisktidsskrift/article/view/54223/72899|journal=Historisk Tidsskrift|volume=4 r\u00e6kke, 3 bind|pages=|via=Historisk Tidsskrift}}</ref>) and there is no evidence of extramarital affairs on the part of either spouse. <ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\" /> Their marriage is described as having been harmonious. <ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> All of their children were sent to live with her parents in Mecklenburg for the first years of their lives, with the possible exception of the last son, Hans, as it was the belief at the time that the parents would indulge their children too much.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She showed a keen interest in science and visited the astronomer [[Tycho Brahe]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She was also interested in the old songs of [[folklore]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/>\n\nShe proved a diligent matchmaker. Her daughter, [[Anne of Denmark]], would marry [[James VI of Scotland]] and become queen consort in 1589. She arranged the marriage against the will of the Council.\n\n==Regency==\nQueen Sophie had no political power during the lifetime of her spouse.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> When her underage son [[Christian IV]] became king in 1588, she was given no place in the regency council in Denmark itself.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> From 1590, however, she acted as regent for the duchies of [[Schleswig-Holstein]] for her son.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/>\n\nShe organised a grand funeral for her spouse, arranged for the dowries for her daughters and for her own allowance, all independently and against the will of the council.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She engaged in a power struggle with the regents of Denmark and with the Council of State, which had Christian declared of age in 1593.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She wished the duchies to be divided between her younger sons, which caused a conflict.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> Sophie only gave up her position the following year, 1594. As such, she came into conflict with the government, which exiled her to the Palace of [[Nyk\u00f6ping Castle|Nyk\u00f8bing Slot]] on the island of [[Falster]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She spent her time there in the study of [[chemistry]], [[astronomy]] and other sciences.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She also renovated Nyk\u00f8bing Slot.\n\n==Later life==\nThe Dowager Queen Sophie managed her estates in [[Lolland]]-Falster so well that her son could borrow money from her on several occasions for his wars.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She also engaged in large-scale trade and in money-lending.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> She often visited Mecklenburg, and attended her daughter's wedding in [[Dresden]] in 1602. In 1603 she became involved in an inheritance dispute with her uncle, which remained unsolved at his death in 1610.<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> In 1608, she managed to soften the punishment of [[Rigborg Brockenhuus]], and in 1628, she was one of the influential people who prevented her son from having her grandson's lover, [[Anne Lykke]], accused of [[witchcraft]].<ref name=\"Dansk Kvindebiografisk Leksikon\"/> Sophie died in [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster]] at the age of seventy-four as the richest woman in Northern Europe.\n\n==Issue==\n#  [[Elisabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Braunshweig|Elizabeth]] (25 August 1573 \u2013 19 June 1626), married in 1590 to [[Henry Julius, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]].\n# [[Anne of Denmark|Anne]] (12 December 1574 \u2013 2 March 1619), married on 23 November 1589 to King [[James I of England|James VI of Scotland (later James I of England)]]\n# [[Christian IV of Denmark and Norway]] (12 April 1577 \u2013 28 February 1648)\n# [[Ulrik of Denmark (1578\u20131624)|Ulrik]] (30 December 1578 \u2013 27 March 1624 in [[R\u00fchn]]), last [[Bishop of Schleswig|Bishop of the old Schleswig see]] (1602\u20131624), and as Ulrich II [[Diocesan administrator#Administrators of prince-bishoprics|Lutheran Administrator]] of the [[Bishopric of Schwerin|Prince-Bishopric of Schwerin]] (1603\u20131624), married with Lady Catherine [[von Hahn|Hahn]]-Hinrichshagen\n# John August (1579\u20131579), died in infancy\n# [[Augusta of Denmark|Augusta]] (8 April 1580 \u2013 5 February 1639), married on 30 August 1596 to Duke [[Johann Adolf of Holstein-Gottorp]]\n# [[Hedwig of Denmark|Hedwig]] (5 August 1581 \u2013 26 November 1641), married on 12 September 1602 to [[Christian II, Elector of Saxony]]\n# [[John, Prince of Schleswig-Holstein]] (9 July 1583 \u2013 28 October 1602)\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{see also|Mecklenburg Ancestral Table}}\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow'''\n|2= 2. [[Ulrich III, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|3= 3. [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n|4= 4. [[Albrecht VII, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|5= 5. [[Anna of Brandenburg, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Anna of Brandenburg]]\n|6= 6. [[Frederick I of Denmark]]\n|7= 7. [[Sophie of Pomerania]]\n|8= 8. [[Magnus II, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|9= 9. [[Sophie of Pomerania-Stettin|Sophie of Pomerania]]\n|10= 10. [[Joachim I Nestor, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n|11= 11. [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Electress of Brandenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]]\n|12= 12. [[Christian I of Denmark]]\n|13= 13. [[Dorothea of Brandenburg]]\n|14= 14. [[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania]]\n|15= 15. [[Anna Jagiellon, Duchess of Pomerania|Anna Jagiellon]]\n|16= 16. [[Henry IV, Duke of Mecklenburg]]\n|17= 17. [[Dorothea of Brandenburg, Duchess of Mecklenburg|Dorothea of Brandenburg]]\n|18= 18. [[Eric II, Duke of Pomerania]] (=#28)\n|19= 19. [[Sophia of Pomerania-Stolp]] (=#29)\n|20= 20. [[John Cicero, Elector of Brandenburg]]\n|21= 21. [[Margaret of Thuringia]]\n|22= 22. [[John of Denmark]]\n|23= 23. [[Christina of Saxony]]\n|24= 24. [[Dietrich, Count of Oldenburg]]\n|25= 25. [[Helvig of Schauenburg]]\n|26= 26. [[John, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach]]\n|27= 27. [[Barbara of Saxe-Wittenberg]]\n|28= 28. [[Eric II, Duke of Pomerania]] (=#18)\n|29= 29. [[Sophia of Pomerania-Stolp]] (=#19)\n|30= 30. [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]]\n|31= 31. [[Elizabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)|Elizabeth of Austria]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Sophie of Mecklenburg-G\u00fcstrow, Queen of Denmark}}\n* [http://www.kongernessamling.dk/en/rosenborg/person/sophie/ Queen Sophie] at the website of the [[Royal Danish Collection]]\n*http://www.guide2womenleaders.com/womeninpower/Womeninpower1570.htm\n*http://www.thepeerage.com/p10139.htm\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Mecklenburg-Schwerin]]|4 September|1557|14 October|1631|[[House of Mecklenburg]]}}\n{{S-roy|dk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Dorothea of Saxe-Lauenburg]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Danish consorts|Queen consort of Denmark]] and [[List of Norwegian consorts|Norway]]|years=1572\u20131588}}\n{{S-af