{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uzbekistan", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Uzbekistan}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Uzbekistan\n}}\n{{infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uzbekistan\n| map1            = {{location map|Uzbekistan |relief=  |lon_deg = 62.58911133 |lat_deg = 80.98399427 |mark= |width=300px |caption=}}\n| legend1         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Uzbekistan]]\n| first_case      = [[Tashkent]]\n| arrival_date    = 15 March 2020<br/>''''' ({{age in years, months, weeks and days|2020|03|15}})'''''\n| date            = \n| origin          = [[France]], [[Turkey]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Switzerland]]\n| confirmed_cases = 221<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 koronavirus infeksiyasi |url=http://coronavirus.uz/uz |publisher=[[Ministry of Public Health (Uzbekistan)|Ministry of Health (Uzbekistan)]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=uz}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 25<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\" />\n| deaths          = 2<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\" />\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Uzbekistan]] when its first case was confirmed on 15 March 2020. The case is a Uzbek citizen returning from France. Uzbekistan's Health Ministry has a list of people who were in contact with the victim, with plans to quarantine them. After the case was announced, Kazakh President [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] announced a state of emergency in [[Kazakhstan]], and promptly closed the border with Uzbekistan. Two days before the first case of coronavirus, Uzbekistan suspended flights to [[France]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]]. On 22 March 2020, Uzbekistan ordered companies in [[Tashkent]] to do remote working, as well as making protective masks mandatory. On March 27, 2020, the first death was reported in the country, who was a 72-year-old woman.\n\nAs of 3 April, there have been 221 confirmed cases, 25 recoveries and 2 deaths.\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 28 February 2020, [[Uzbekistan Airways]] suspended flights to [[Jeddah]] and [[Medina]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seyfaddini |first1=Ilkin |title=Uzbekistan Airways suspends flights to Jeddah, Medina |url=https://en.trend.az/business/transport/3199017.html |website=en.trend.az |date=28 February 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322182449/https://en.trend.az/business/transport/3199017.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 13 March 2020, Uzbekistan suspended flights to [[France]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Uzbekistan suspends flights to and from France, Spain and UK |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-suspends-flights-to-and-from-france-spain-and-uk-idUSL8N2B67HZ |website=reuters.com |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322182027/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-suspends-flights-to-and-from-france-spain-and-uk-idUSL8N2B67HZ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days later, the country confirmed its first case of coronavirus, who was an Uzbek citizen returning from France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-govt-idUSL8N2B802F |title=Uzbekistan confirms first coronavirus case - govt |work=Reuters |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319023808/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-govt-idUSL8N2B802F |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Uzbekistan's Health Ministry published a list of people who were in contact with the victim, with plans to quarantine them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/uzbekistan-confirms-its-first-coronavirus-case/1766896|title=Uzbekistan confirms its first coronavirus case|website=aa.com.tr|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319054401/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/uzbekistan-confirms-its-first-coronavirus-case/1766896|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After the case was announced, [[President of Kazakhstan|Kazakh President]] [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] announced a state of emergency in [[Kazakhstan]], and promptly closed the border with Uzbekistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/kazakhstan-uzbekistan-close-borders-after-first-coronavirus-cases|title=Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan close borders after first coronavirus cases |work=National Post|agency=Reuters|date=15 March 2020|language=en-CA|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, the government announced that entertainment venues and tea houses would be closed and large weddings and other family gatherings would be prohibited.<ref>{{cite news |title=Central Asia tightens restrictions as coronavirus spreads |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-centralasia/central-asia-tightens-restrictions-as-coronavirus-spreads-idUSKBN218090 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Reuters |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020, Uzbekistan ordered companies in [[Tashkent]] to do remote working, as well as making protective masks mandatory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uzbekistan makes masks, remote work mandatory in capital |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-idUSL8N2BF0JZ |website=reuters.com |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322181619/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-idUSL8N2BF0JZ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, the [[Government of Uzbekistan|Uzbekistan government]] announced that a lockdown of Tashkent would start on the next day as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/23/world/asia/23reuters-health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-lockdown.html |title = Uzbekistan to Lock Down Capital Tashkent Due to Coronavirus|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, the first death was reported in the country; that of a 72-year-old woman who had underlying health conditions and suffered a [[heart attack]]. She was appeared to have been infected by her daughter who had recently returned from [[Turkey]].<ref name=firstdeath>{{cite news |last1=News Desk |title=Uzbekistan reports first coronavirus death as it widens lockdowns |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/27/uzbekistan-reports-first-coronavirus-death-as-it-widens-lockdowns.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[The Jakarta Post]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/28/world/asia/28reuters-health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-death.html Uzbek Doctor, 39, Dies After Coronavirus Self-Treatment]</ref> the second death was also confirmed.  A doctor in Uzbekistan died on Saturday after unsuccessfully trying to treat a coronavirus infection that he kept secret, the Central Asian nation's healthcare ministry said.\nThe 39-year-old man had been in contact with Uzbek \"patient zero\", it said in a statement, who appeared to have infected him.\nHe was hospitalized on March 26 in grave condition and died two days later, becoming the second coronavirus patient to die in Uzbekistan.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n\n==References==\n<references />{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Uzbekistan|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Uzbekistan]]\n\n{{uzbekistan-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Uzbekistan}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Uzbekistan\n}}\n{{infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uzbekistan\n| map1            = {{location map|Uzbekistan |relief=  |lon_deg = 62.58911133 |lat_deg = 80.98399427 |mark= |width=300px |caption=}}\n| legend1         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Uzbekistan]]\n| first_case      = [[Tashkent]]\n| arrival_date    = 15 March 2020<br/>''''' ({{age in years, months, weeks and days|2020|03|15}})'''''\n| date            = \n| origin          = [[France]], [[Turkey]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Switzerland]]\n| confirmed_cases = 221<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 koronavirus infeksiyasi |url=http://coronavirus.uz/uz |publisher=[[Ministry of Public Health (Uzbekistan)|Ministry of Health (Uzbekistan)]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=uz}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 25<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\" />\n| deaths          = 2<ref name=\"official-stats-uz\" />\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Uzbekistan]] when its first case was confirmed on 15 March 2020. The case is a Uzbek citizen returning from France. Uzbekistan's Health Ministry has a list of people who were in contact with the victim, with plans to quarantine them. After the case was announced, Kazakh President [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] announced a state of emergency in [[Kazakhstan]], and promptly closed the border with Uzbekistan. Two days before the first case of coronavirus, Uzbekistan suspended flights to [[France]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]]. On 22 March 2020, Uzbekistan ordered companies in [[Tashkent]] to do remote working, as well as making protective masks mandatory. On March 27, 2020, the first death was reported in the country, who was a 72-year-old woman.\n\nAs of 3 April, there have been 221 confirmed cases, 25 recoveries and 2 deaths.\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 28 February 2020, [[Uzbekistan Airways]] suspended flights to [[Jeddah]] and [[Medina]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seyfaddini |first1=Ilkin |title=Uzbekistan Airways suspends flights to Jeddah, Medina |url=https://en.trend.az/business/transport/3199017.html |website=en.trend.az |date=28 February 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322182449/https://en.trend.az/business/transport/3199017.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 13 March 2020, Uzbekistan suspended flights to [[France]], [[Spain]], and the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Uzbekistan suspends flights to and from France, Spain and UK |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-suspends-flights-to-and-from-france-spain-and-uk-idUSL8N2B67HZ |website=reuters.com |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322182027/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-suspends-flights-to-and-from-france-spain-and-uk-idUSL8N2B67HZ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days later, the country confirmed its first case of coronavirus, who was an Uzbek citizen returning from France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-govt-idUSL8N2B802F |title=Uzbekistan confirms first coronavirus case - govt |work=Reuters |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319023808/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan/uzbekistan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-govt-idUSL8N2B802F |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Uzbekistan's Health Ministry published a list of people who were in contact with the victim, with plans to quarantine them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/uzbekistan-confirms-its-first-coronavirus-case/1766896|title=Uzbekistan confirms its first coronavirus case|website=aa.com.tr|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319054401/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/uzbekistan-confirms-its-first-coronavirus-case/1766896|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After the case was announced, [[President of Kazakhstan|Kazakh President]] [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] announced a state of emergency in [[Kazakhstan]], and promptly closed the border with Uzbekistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/kazakhstan-uzbekistan-close-borders-after-first-coronavirus-cases|title=Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan close borders after first coronavirus cases |work=National Post|agency=Reuters|date=15 March 2020|language=en-CA|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, the government announced that entertainment venues and tea houses would be closed and and large weddings and other family gatherings would be prohibited.<ref>{{cite news |title=Central Asia tightens restrictions as coronavirus spreads |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-centralasia/central-asia-tightens-restrictions-as-coronavirus-spreads-idUSKBN218090 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=Reuters |date=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March 2020, Uzbekistan ordered companies in [[Tashkent]] to do remote working, as well as making protective masks mandatory.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uzbekistan makes masks, remote work mandatory in capital |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-idUSL8N2BF0JZ |website=reuters.com |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322181619/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-idUSL8N2BF0JZ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, the [[Government of Uzbekistan|Uzbekistan government]] announced that a lockdown of Tashkent would start on the next day as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/23/world/asia/23reuters-health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-lockdown.html |title = Uzbekistan to Lock Down Capital Tashkent Due to Coronavirus|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, the first death was reported in the country; that of a 72-year-old woman who had underlying health conditions and suffered a [[heart attack]]. She was appeared to have been infected by her daughter who had recently returned from [[Turkey]].<ref name=firstdeath>{{cite news |last1=News Desk |title=Uzbekistan reports first coronavirus death as it widens lockdowns |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/27/uzbekistan-reports-first-coronavirus-death-as-it-widens-lockdowns.html |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=[[The Jakarta Post]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/28/world/asia/28reuters-health-coronavirus-uzbekistan-death.html Uzbek Doctor, 39, Dies After Coronavirus Self-Treatment]</ref> the second death was also confirmed.  A doctor in Uzbekistan died on Saturday after unsuccessfully trying to treat a coronavirus infection that he kept secret, the Central Asian nation's healthcare ministry said.\nThe 39-year-old man had been in contact with Uzbek \"patient zero\", it said in a statement, who appeared to have infected him.\nHe was hospitalized on March 26 in grave condition and died two days later, becoming the second coronavirus patient to die in Uzbekistan.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n\n==References==\n<references />{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Uzbekistan|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Uzbekistan]]\n\n{{uzbekistan-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Uzbekistan"}
{"title_page": "Ludhiana", "text_new": "{{short description|Metropolis in Punjab, India}}\n{{About|the municipality in Punjab, India|its namesake district|Ludhiana district}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n{{original research|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Ludhiana <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolis]]\n| image_skyline                   = Ludhiana Montage.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Gurudwara Sri Dukhniwaran Sahib, Clock Tower, Gurudwara Shri Manji Sahib Alamgir, Lodhi Fort, Maharaja Ranjit Singh War Museum, Shri Krishna Mandir and Guru Nanak Dev Bhavan, Tiger Safari\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Punjab#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|30.91|75.85|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of Punjab, India|District]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Ludhiana district|Ludhiana]]\n| subdivision_name3               = Ludhiana West\nLudhiana East\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| government_type                 = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013Council]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Ludhiana Municipal Corporation]]\n| leader_party                    = [[Indian National Congress|INC]]\n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor of Mumbai|Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Balkar Sandhu<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhardwaj |first1=Nidhi |title=Balkar sandhu becomes mayor of Ludhiana {{!}} Ludhiana News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/balkar-sandhu-becomes-mayor-of-ludhiana/articleshow/63463203.cms |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=26 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| unit_pref                       = Metri\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 310\n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 262\n| population_total                = 1,618,879\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\":0\"/>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = [[List of most populous cities in India|22nd]]\n| population_demonym              = Ludhianvi\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = Multiple 141001-141016\n| area_code                       = 0161\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = PB-10, PB-91\n| website                         = http://www.ludhiana.nic.in/\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Ludhiana''' is a city and a [[municipal corporation]] in [[Ludhiana district]] in the Indian state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].\n\nLudhiana is Punjab's largest city and India's largest city north of [[Delhi]], with an area of 310 &nbsp;sq.&nbsp;km and an estimated population of 1,618,879 {{as of|2011|alt=as of the}} [[2011 Indian census|2011 census]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The city stands on the [[Sutlej River]]'s old bank, {{convert|13|km}} south of its present course. It is an industrial center of northern India; the UK's BBC has called it India's Manchester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2006/02/28/280206_ludhiana_manchester_feature.shtml|title=India's Manchester|work=BBC|date=28 February 2006|access-date=25 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140818191404/http://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2006/02/28/280206_ludhiana_manchester_feature.shtml|archive-date=18 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Ludhiana was among the list of smart cities that will be developed by government of India. Ludhiana is the easiest city in [[India]] to do business according to the World Bank. It is ranked first in paying taxes, second in resolving insolvency, fourth in contract enforcement, and seventh in starting a business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doingbusiness.org/en/data/exploreeconomies/sub|title=Sub National|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLudhiana is {{convert|107|km}} west of the state capital, [[Chandigarh]], on NH 95, and is centrally located on [[National Highway 44 (India)|National Highway 44]], which runs from [[New Delhi]] to [[Amritsar]]. It is 315&nbsp;km (194 miles) north of [[Delhi]] and 142&nbsp;km (88 miles) southeast of [[Amritsar]].\n\n==Geography==\nLudhiana is located at {{Coord|30.9|N|75.85|E}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/23/Ludhiana.html|title=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc&nbsp;\u2013 Ludhiana|work=fallingrain.com|access-date=8 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080529001025/http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/23/Ludhiana.html|archive-date=29 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> It has an average elevation of 244&nbsp;metres (798&nbsp;ft). Ludhiana City, to its residents, consists of the Old City and the New City (or the residential and official quarters of the colonial British encampment, traditionally known as Civil Lines; this is as opposed to the Army Lines, which are no longer extant as the British Cantonment was abandoned in 1845).\n\nThe land dips steeply to the north and the west where, before 1785, the river [[Sutlej]] ran.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe Old Fort was at the banks of the Sutlej (and now houses the College of Textile Engineering). Legend has it that a tunnel connects it to the fort in [[Phillaur]]&nbsp;\u2013 although why this should be is debatable, as the Sutlej was the traditional dividing line between the principalities, often occupied by enemy forces (see History section).\n\nThe ground is of yellow sandstone and granite, forming small hillocks, plateaus and dips.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe tree of largest natural extraction was the kikar, or Acacia indica, but has been supplanted by the eucalyptus, transplanted from rural Australia in the late 1950s by the government of Chief Minister [[Pratap Singh Kairon]].\n\nGulmohars and jacarandas were planted by the British along the avenues of Civil Lines, as were other flowering trees, while the Old City contains almost no vegetation or parks, except for a few isolated [[Ficus religiosa|pipal]] trees, holy to the Hindus, as it is supposed to be the abode of Lord Shiva.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Climate==\nLudhiana features a [[semi-arid]] climate under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], with three defined seasons; summer, monsoon and winter. Ludhiana on average sees roughly {{convert|809.3|mm|in}} of precipitation annually. The official weather station for the city is in the compound of the Civil Surgeon's Office to the west of Ludhiana. Weather records here data back to 1 August 1868.\n\nLudhiana has one of the worst air pollution problems in India, with particulate matter being over six times the [[World Health Organization]] recommended standard, making it the 13th most polluted city in the world.<ref name=\"Majeed\">{{Cite news|author=Majeed, Shariq |date=26 March 2014 |title=Ludhiana worries over its PM |newspaper=The Times of India |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-worries-over-its-PM/articleshow/32709885.cms |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327153327/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-worries-over-its-PM/articleshow/32709885.cms |archivedate=27 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Preet, Jatinder|date=16 October 2011|title=Ludhiana fourth most polluted city in the world|location=Delhi, India|newspaper=The Sunday Guardian|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/news/ludhiana-fourth-most-polluted-city-in-the-world|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412184445/http://www.sunday-guardian.com/news/ludhiana-fourth-most-polluted-city-in-the-world|archivedate=12 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Industrial water pollution is also of significant concern in portions of Ludhiana, notably along the [[Buddha Nullah|Budha Dariya]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=1 December 2013|title=How air and water pollution plagues Indian cities|newspaper=Hindustan Times|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-air-and-water-pollution-plagues-indian-cities/article1-1157717.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129025745/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-air-and-water-pollution-plagues-indian-cities/article1-1157717.aspx|archivedate=29 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n| location = Ludhiana (1868-2008; relative humidity 1961-1990)\n| metric first = Y\n| single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 29\n|Feb record high C = 30.4\n|Mar record high C = 36.3\n|Apr record high C = 43.4\n|May record high C = 46.6\n|Jun record high C = 46.6\n|Jul record high C = 43.2\n|Aug record high C = 39.8\n|Sep record high C = 37.9\n|Oct record high C = 36\n|Nov record high C = 35.1\n|Dec record high C = 27.9\n|year record high C = 46.6\n| Jan avg record high C = 23.8\n| Feb avg record high C = 26.9\n| Mar